Sure, here's a detailed step-by-step guide on building the backend server for your Business Directory Listing app with ExpressJS and Dart:

1. Set up the project environment
   - Install Node.js on your machine (if not installed already)
   - Create a new directory for your project and navigate to it in the terminal
   - Run `npm init` to create a `package.json` file and follow the prompts to fill in the details

2. Set up the project dependencies
   - Run `npm install express cors body-parser firebase-admin --save` to install the required dependencies
   - The `express` module will be used to create the server and handle API requests
   - The `cors` module will allow cross-origin requests from your frontend
   - The `body-parser` module will parse the request body which is sent from frontend
   - The `firebase-admin` module will be used to authenticate users and interact with Firestore database

3. Create a `server.js` file
   - Create a new file named `server.js` in the root directory of your project
   - Import the required modules:

     ```javascript
     const express = require('express');  // Import Express
     const cors = require('cors');  // Import Cors middleware
     const bodyParser = require('body-parser');  // Import Body Parser middleware
     const admin = require('firebase-admin');  // Import Firebase Admin
     const { firestore } = require('firebase-admin');  // Import Firestore
     ```

   - Create a new Express app instance and add middleware:

     ```javascript
     const app = express();
     app.use(cors());
     app.use(bodyParser.json());
     ```

   - Initialize Firebase Admin with your service account credentials:

     ```javascript
     const serviceAccount = require("./path/to/serviceAccountKey.json");  // Replace with path to your serviceAccountKey.json file
     admin.initializeApp({
       credential: admin.credential.cert(serviceAccount)
     });
     ```

   - Get a reference to the Firestore database:

     ```javascript
     const db = admin.firestore();
     ```

4. Add API endpoints for handling Business queries
   - Create a router instance using Express and export it for use in the `server.js` file:

     ```javascript
     const businessRoutes = express.Router();
     module.exports = businessRoutes;
     ```

   - Add endpoint for getting all businesses:

     ```javascript
     businessRoutes.get('/businesses', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         const businesses = [];
         const snapshot = await db.collection('Businesses').get();
         snapshot.forEach(doc => {
           const businessData = doc.data();
           businesses.push({...businessData, id: doc.id});
         });
         res.status(200).json(businesses);
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

   - Add endpoint for getting a single business by ID:

     ```javascript
     businessRoutes.get('/businesses/:id', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         const snapshot = await db.collection('Businesses').doc(req.params.id).get();
         if (!snapshot.exists) {
           return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Business not found' });
         }
         const businessData = snapshot.data();
         res.status(200).json({ ...businessData, id: snapshot.id });
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

   - Add endpoint for creating a new business:

     ```javascript
     businessRoutes.post('/businesses', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         const data = req.body;
         const ref = await db.collection('Businesses').add(data);
         res.status(201).json({ id: ref.id });
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

   - Add endpoint for updating an existing business:

     ```javascript
     businessRoutes.put('/businesses/:id', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         const data = req.body;
         await db.collection('Businesses').doc(req.params.id).update(data);
         res.status(200).json({ message: 'Business updated successfully' });
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

   - Add endpoint for deleting a business:

     ```javascript
     businessRoutes.delete('/businesses/:id', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         await db.collection('Businesses').doc(req.params.id).delete();
         res.status(200).json({ message: 'Business deleted successfully' });
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

5. Add API endpoints for handling Reviews queries
   - Create a router instance using Express and export it for use in the `server.js` file:

     ```javascript
     const reviewRoutes = express.Router();
     module.exports = reviewRoutes;
     ```

   - Add endpoint for getting all reviews for a business:

     ```javascript
     reviewRoutes.get('/businesses/:id/reviews', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         const reviews = [];
         const snapshot = await db.collection('Businesses').doc(req.params.id).collection('Reviews').get();
         snapshot.forEach(doc => {
           const reviewData = doc.data();
           reviews.push({ ...reviewData, id: doc.id });
         });
         res.status(200).json(reviews);
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

   - Add endpoint for getting a single review for a business:

     ```javascript
     reviewRoutes.get('/businesses/:business_id/reviews/:id', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         const snapshot = await db.collection('Businesses').doc(req.params.business_id).collection('Reviews').doc(req.params.id).get();
         if (!snapshot.exists) {
           return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Review not found' });
         }
         const reviewData = snapshot.data();
         res.status(200).json({ ...reviewData, id: snapshot.id });
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

   - Add endpoint for creating a new review for a business:

     ```javascript
     reviewRoutes.post('/businesses/:id/reviews', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         const data = req.body;
         const ref = await db.collection('Businesses').doc(req.params.id).collection('Reviews').add(data);
         res.status(201).json({ id: ref.id });
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

   - Add endpoint for updating an existing review for a business:

     ```javascript
     reviewRoutes.put('/businesses/:business_id/reviews/:id', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         const data = req.body;
         await db.collection('Businesses').doc(req.params.business_id).collection('Reviews').doc(req.params.id).update(data);
         res.status(200).json({ message: 'Review updated successfully' });
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

   - Add endpoint for deleting a review for a business:

     ```javascript
     reviewRoutes.delete('/businesses/:business_id/reviews/:id', async (req, res) => {
       try {
         await db.collection('Businesses').doc(req.params.business_id).collection('Reviews').doc(req.params.id).delete();
         res.status(200).json({ message: 'Review deleted successfully' });
       } catch (error) {
         console.log(error);
         res.status(500).json({ error: error.message });
       }
     });
     ```

6. Mount the API routes in `server.js`
   - Import the router instances at the top of the `server.js` file:

     ```javascript
     const businessRoutes = require('./businessRoutes');
     const reviewRoutes = require('./reviewRoutes');
     ```

   - Mount them using `app.use()` method:

     ```javascript
     app.use('/api', businessRoutes);
     app.use('/api', reviewRoutes);
     ```

7. Start the server
   - Add the following code in the `server.js` file at the end:

     ```javascript
     const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;

     app.listen(PORT, () => {
       console.log(`Server listening on port ${PORT}`);
     });
     ```

   - Run the server using `node server.js` command in the terminal
   - You should see the message "Server listening on port 3000" in the console

That's it! You have now successfully built the backend server for your Business Directory Listing app using ExpressJS and Firebase. You can now move ahead with frontend development to connect your Flutter app to this backend.
